Time Series¶

    1. Data with a time index.
    1. An attempt at measuring a dynamical system.

Data is the window we have to understand the underlying dynamics of the system we are studying.

First stop are ARIMA → and they can take you very far - Light - Robust - Interpretable (Often you can find a direct link between an ARIMA model and a physical system)

ARIMA models belong to the family of statistical models - Data are realizations of random variables, which are characterized by an underlying distribution (which we typically assume is Gaussian) - This opens the possibility of using statistical tools for analysis (For instance, correlation) - Random variables are characterized by static parameters → we want stationarity (what is stationarity) - Differencing

Statistical models rely on the study of the residuals, which are the difference between our observations and model predictions. They are also a random variable.

In [22]:
plot_timeseries(train, target_label, "X [...]")
In [57]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(6, 2.5))
plot_distribution(train, target_label, "X [...]", ax=ax)
  • A time series is a collection of time-indexed samples which are drawn from an underlying distribution
  • If we are able to parametrize such distribution, we will be able to predict future values of the time series

Stationarity¶

A characteristic of a time series that guarantees that its statistical properties do not change over time.

The consumption is clearly non-stationary

  • It shows (at least) two distinct behaviours → this suggests a seasonal pattern
In [27]:

Modelling with ARIMA¶

A family of models/methods that aims at expressing a time series as a combination of the following components:

AR (Auto-Regressive)
☑ I (Integrated)
MA (Moving Average)

Assumptions:

  • Everything is linear
  • Everything is Gaussian

But first: Correlation¶

It is a measure of how (linearly) related two random variables are.

In [32]:
y1 = np.random.normal(0, 1, n)
y2 = 2 * y1 + np.random.normal(1, 1, n)
y3 = 0.2 * y1 + np.random.normal(0, 1, n)
In [33]:
plot_rvs(y1, y2, y3)

But remember that I can have random variables that are time-indexed.

In [34]:
lag = 10
y4 = y1[lag:] + np.random.normal(0, 0.3, n - lag)
In [35]:
plot_rv_with_lags(y1, y4, lag)

In a time series context, past values of a random variable can be considered another random variable

  • Are present values of a series (cor)related to its past values?
    • Then we say that variable is autocorrelated (e.g. the _Random Walk: $Y_t = Y_{t-1} + \epsilon_{t}$)

...back to modelling¶

We can check if the consumption is autocorrelated by investigating the ACF and PACF

In [48]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, sharey=True, figsize=(8, 2.5))
plot_acf(target.values, ax=axes[0]), plot_pacf(target.values, ax=axes[1])
add_arrows(axes[0])
_, _ = plt.tight_layout(), plt.show()

In a nutshell, you need to look at the peaks:

  • There is a clear peak at lag 1 (and at lag 7)
  • ACF and PACF are complementary functions that provide information which gives an idea of which ARIMA model might be more suitable.

☑ AR (Auto-Regressive) → $Y_t = \overbrace{\theta_1 Y_{t-1} + \cdots + \theta_i Y_{t-i}}^{p} + \epsilon_{t}$
☑ MA (Moving Average) → $Y_t = \epsilon_{t} + \overbrace{\theta_1\epsilon_{t-1} + \cdots + \theta_i\epsilon_{t-i}}^{q}$

In [38]:
p, d, q = (1, 0, 1)  # Based on ACF and PACF
mod = ARIMA(endog=target, order=(p, d, q), freq="D", trend="n")
res = mod.fit()
show_results_as_html(res, 0)

(!) AIC and BIC are statistical tests to evaluate the performance of the model

Ultimately, the model is evaluated checking whether its residuals behave like independent and identically distributed Gaussian white noise.

Workflow summary¶

Conclusion¶

  • "Everything" is a random variable
  • Statistical models are a solid first step
    • Lightweight and robust (and probabilistic)
  • Much of this workflow are transferable to other models
    • E.g. adding lagged variables as features
    • E.g. using differences as target
  • The methods are modular and transparent, helping with interpretability
  • Statistical methods allow quantifying modelling success

Thank you ¶

Concepts worth investigating further

  • Main python package used in this talk: statsmodels
    • Honorable mentions: darts, AutoARIMA
  • Relevant concepts:
    • Power transformations: Box-Cox transformation
    • Time series decomposition
    • Stationarity: Augmented Dickey-Fuller test
    • Autocorrelation: ACF, PACF
    • Model quality evaluation: AIC, BIC
